      <SupplementalInformationDetail>
        <FormAndLineReferenceDesc>SCHEDULE C, PART II-B, LINE 1</FormAndLineReferenceDesc>
        <ExplanationTxt>1. TESTIMONY IN SUPPORT OF SD2971, AN ACT PROMOTING HOUSING STABILITY AND HOMELESSNESS PREVENTION THROUGH A RIGHT TO COUNSEL PILOT PROGRAM IN MASSACHUSETTS IN RESPONSE TO THE COVID EMERGENCY - SUBMITTED JULY 9, 2020. MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED SUBMITTED LEGISLATIVE TESTIMONY TO CHAIRMAN CRIGHTON, CHAIRMAN HONAN, AND HONORABLE MEMBERS OF THE JOINT COMMITTEE ON HOUSING IN SUPPORT OF A RIGHT TO COUNSEL PILOT PROGRAM WITHIN HOUSING COURT IN RESPONSE TO THE COVID-19 PANDEMIC. THIS LEGISLATION WOULD ALLOW NON- PROFITS TO PROVIDE FULL LEGAL REPRESENTATION IN EVICTION PROCEEDINGS FOR BOTH TENANTS AND LANDLORDS WHOSE INCOMES DO NOT EXCEED 200% OF THE FEDERAL POVERTY LEVEL. OUR TESTIMONY HIGHLIGHTED THAT BEFORE THE COVID-19 PANDEMIC, 92% OF TENANTS FACING EVICTION FROM THEIR HOMES DID NOT HAVE LAWYERS, WHILE 70% OF LANDLORDS HAD REPRESENTATION, AND THAT THIS DISPARITY IS ESPECIALLY PREVALENT IN COMMUNITIES OF COLOR. WE HIGHLIGHTED HOW UPENDING THIS DYNAMIC COULD LEAD TO MEANINGFUL CHANGE, AS A QUINCY, MA STUDY FOUND THAT "TWO- THIRDS OF THE TENANTS WHO RECEIVED FULL REPRESENTATION WERE ABLE TO STAY IN THEIR HOMES, COMPARED WITH ONE-THIRD OF THOSE WHO LACKED REPRESENTATION." LASTLY, OUR TESTIMONY POINTED OUT THAT THIS PILOT PROGRAM WOULD BE FINANCIALLY BENEFICIAL FOR THE COMMONWEALTH, AS A RECENT REPORT FROM THE BOSTON BAR ASSOCIATION HAD ESTIMATED THAT "FOR EVERY DOLLAR SPENT ON FULL LEGAL REPRESENTATION IN EVICTION CASES, THE COMMONWEALTH SAVES APPROXIMATELY 2.40 ON THE DIRECT COSTS ASSOCIATED WITH HOMELESSNESS." BY PASSING THIS LEGISLATION, MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED ARGUED THAT A RIGHT TO COUNSEL PROGRAM COULD PROTECT VULNERABLE COMMUNITIES DURING THE PANDEMIC, AND SERVE AS A COST-EFFECTIVE MEASURE FOR THE STATE. 2. TESTIMONY IN SUPPORT OF IN SUPPORT OF S2820, AN ACT TO REFORM POLICE STANDARDS AND SHIFT RECOURSES TO BUILD A MORE EQUITABLE, FAIR AND JUST COMMONWEALTH THAT VALUES BLACK LIVES AND COMMUNITIES OF COLOR - SUBMITTED ON JULY 16, 2020. MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED SUBMITTED LEGISLATIVE TESTIMONY TO CHAIRMAN MICHLEWITZ, CHAIRWOMAN CRONIN, AND HONORABLE MEMBERS OF THE HOUSE WAYS AND MEANS COMMITTEE AND JOINT JUDICIARY COMMITTEE IN SUPPORT S2820, A POLICE ACCOUNTABILITY BILL. OUR TESTIMONY FOCUSED ON THE YOUTH- SERVING MEASURES OF THIS EXPANSIVE BILL, ADVOCATING FOR ENDING MANDATORY POLICE PLACEMENT IN SCHOOLS, AND ENSURING PUBLIC ACCOUNTABILITY FOR WHAT POLICE DO IN SCHOOLS. IN PARTICULAR, OUR TESTIMONY ADVOCATED FOR THE ADDITION OF FOUR AMENDMENTS THAT WOULD 1) REQUIRE TRAINING AND CERTIFICATION FOR SCHOOL RESOURCE OFFICERS, 2) PUT SCHOOL COMMITTEES - NOT SUPERINTENDENTS AND POLICE CHIEFS - IN CHARGE OF ANNUALLY APPROVING SCHOOL POLICING BY VOTE, 3) PROHIBIT MASSACHUSETTS SCHOOL STAFF AND SCHOOL POLICE FROM SHARING STUDENT INFORMATION TO THE BOSTON REGIONAL INTELLIGENCE CENTER, THE FBI, ICE, AND OTHER GANG DATABASES, AND 4) ALLOW MULTIPLE CASES ON A JUVENILE'S RECORD TO BE CONSIDERED FOR EXPUNGEMENT - RATHER THAN ONLY ONE - AND REDUCE THE LIST OF OFFENSES NEVER ELIGIBLE FOR EXPUNGEMENT. THROUGH ALL OF THESE REQUESTS, MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED URGED THE LEGISLATURE TO END MANDATORY POLICE PLACEMENT IN SCHOOLS AND ENSURE PUBLIC ACCOUNTABILITY FOR WHAT POLICE DO IN SCHOOLS. 3. TESTIMONY IN SUPPORT OF H4829, AN ACT TO IMPROVE AND MODERNIZE THE INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY SYSTEMS AND CAPACITIES OF THE JUDICIARY - SUBMITTED ON JULY 21, 2020. MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED SUBMITTED LEGISLATIVE TESTIMONY TO CHAIRMAN MICHLEWITZ, VICE CHAIRWOMAN GARLICK, AND HONORABLE MEMBERS OF THE HOUSE WAYS AND MEANS COMMITTEE IN SUPPORT OF H4829. THIS BILL WOULD PROVIDE THE FUNDING TO CREATE A STRONGER TECHNOLOGICAL INFRASTRUCTURE WITHIN THE MASSACHUSETTS TRIAL COURT BY ENABLING ELECTRONIC FILE STORAGE AND ELECTRONIC ACCESS TO CASE INFORMATION BY COURT USERS, AND ALLOW COURT USERS TO SUBMIT EVIDENCE ELECTRONICALLY AND DIGITALLY SIGN LEGAL DOCUMENTS. THESE POSSIBILITIES ARE PARTICULARLY IMPORTANT TO MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED, AS WE HAD PREVIOUSLY CONDUCTED EXTENSIVE RESEARCH ON VIRTUAL LEGAL SELF- HELP INITIATIVES ACROSS THE COUNTRY, EXAMINED BEST PRACTICES, AND PUBLISHED A REPORT ON THIS TOPIC. IN 2019, WE RELEASED OUR REPORT TURNING ON THE LIGHTS: HOW THE MASSACHUSETTS TRIAL COURT COULD DEPLOY A VIRTUAL COURT SERVICE CENTER TO ASSIST SELF-REPRESENTED LITIGANTS, WHICH OUTLINED HOW THE TRIAL COURT COULD REPLICATE MANY OF THE SERVICES PROVIDED BY THE EXISTING BRICK-AND-MORTAR COURT SERVICE CENTERS INTO AN INTERACTIVE ONLINE FORMAT. BY MAKING THE COURT SERVICE CENTER RESOURCES AVAILABLE ON A MOBILE FRIENDLY WEBSITE THAT COULD BE ACCESSED ANYWHERE, OUR REPORT FOUND THAT THE TRIAL COURT WOULD SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASE THE NUMBER OF SELF-REPRESENTED LITIGANTS WHO CAN OBTAIN THE HELP THEY NEED. BY FUNDING THESE TYPES OF ESSENTIAL TECHNOLOGICAL IMPROVEMENTS, MASSACHUSETTS APPLESEED ARGUED THAT THE LEGISLATURE WOULD BE ABLE TO SIGNIFICANTLY INCREASE ACCESS TO JUSTICE WITHIN THE COMMONWEALTH.</ExplanationTxt>
      </SupplementalInformationDetail>
